Certainly! Let's refine your CSS to achieve the desired layout using Flexbox. The goal is to have the items evenly spaced and centered within the container. Here's how you can adjust your code:

### CSS
```css
.project-gallery {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
  justify-content: center; /* Center items horizontally */
  gap: 20px; /* Space between items */
  padding: 20px; /* Optional: Add padding around the container */
}

.project-gallery-item {
  flex: 1 1 calc(33.333% - 40px); /* Adjust width to account for margins */
  max-width: calc(33.333% - 40px); /* Ensure items don't exceed container width */
  margin: 10px;
  background-color: #f0f0f0;
  padding: 20px;
  border: 1px solid #ddd;
  border-radius: 10px;
  box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
  text-align: center; /* Center text within each item */
}
```

### HTML
```html
<div class="project-gallery">
  <div class="project-gallery-item">Item 1</div>
  <div class="project-gallery-item">Item 2</div>
  <div class="project-gallery-item">Item 3</div>
  <div class="project-gallery-item">Item 4</div>
  <div class="project-gallery-item">Item 5</div>
  <div class="project-gallery-item">Item 6</div>
</div>
```

### Explanation

1. **Flexbox Properties**:
   - `display: flex;`: Enables Flexbox on the container.
   - `flex-wrap: wrap;`: Allows items to wrap onto multiple lines if necessary.
   - `justify-content: center;`: Centers the items horizontally within the container.
   - `gap: 20px;`: Adds space between items, which is a shorthand for `margin`.

2. **Item Properties**:
   - `flex: 1 1 calc(33.333% - 40px);`: Ensures each item takes up approximately one-third of the container width, accounting for the margins.
   - `max-width: calc(33.333% - 40px);`: Limits the maximum width of each item to prevent overflow.
   - `margin: 10px;`: Adds space around each item.
   - `text-align: center;`: Centers the text within each item.

### Example

